Booleans are simply a check for is something true or false or 0 or 1.





TL:DR of booleans for Dummies and quick usage examples:

!                   you can use Exclamation point to say if check for false 
                    example:
                    
                    bool wasTrue= false;
                    if(!wasTrue)
                    the if statements reads if wasTrue equals false;
                    
bool nothingInitializedInCode;
                    
                    *if you put nothing java will set this to default false; 

Values of Booleans:
"True" or "False"       Bool thisIsABool= true;   if(thisIsABool) return; *works because if statements a bool comparison.
"1"    or "0"           


Valid operators: 
||           Bool thisIsTheRealLife = true; Bool isThisJustFantasy = false;  
            if(thisIsTheRealLife || isThisJustFantasy)   *you can or statement between bools
                
            *reads: " if this isTheRealLife is true or isThisJustFantasy is true then..." 
            
            remember that each is its own check against true unless specified as such
            if(thisIsTheRealLife==false || isThisJustFantasy==false)
            
            or              both of these are the same
            
            if(!thisIsTheRealLife || !isThisJustFantasy) 
               

&&           Bool peanutButter = true; Bool jelly = false;  
            if(peanutButter && jelly)   *you can or statement between bools
                
            *reads: if peanutButter is true and jelly is true then..."
            this statement does not interate because both are not true since jelly is false unless you do it like so:
             if(peanutButter && !jelly) 
             
            again adding !  reverses the logic from checking for true to false

==          bool twin1= true; bool twin2=true;
            if(twin1 == twin2)
            
            reads if twin1 is true and twin2 is true then execute w.e

*though == is sometimes redundant since bools are a test of true or false


